history.content: I'm taking it without 53, but I took multivariable many years back and remember very vaguely the main concepts. I would suggest somewhat reviewing multivariable calc (derivs, grads, and stuff). Obviously, the more you know, the better, but if you have even a fuzzy idea, you can probably pull through. So basically, you can.

children.subject: I definitely don't have Math 53 multivariable experience is what I was trying to say, but I had a general understanding of what multivariable calculus is. So I can't give the perspective of what it's like taking 189 with zero math 53 experience, but rather the perspective of someone who has just a very vague / broad understanding of 53, if that makes sense. If you self-study a bit, you should be fine. If you don't, you will need to learn really quickly in 189.

For example, if you have no idea what a gradient is, you'll be really confused. If you're not great with vector calculus but you know what a gradient is, you can make your way through, but obviously questions with derivatives / gradients may require more time or searching for formulas.

The students' answer is useful info, but your taking multivariable at all before taking the class doesn't help me answer: "can I take 189 without ever having taken 53 in previous semesters, and without taking 53 the same semester as 189?" 
I can definitely self study for 53-content over 2021 summer.
The multivariable calc portion from 127 is more useful than Math 53 Refer to those notes and discussion worksheets and you'll be fine
